description.narrative:
IFC and the Embassy have started partnership on the project: Georgia Agrubusiness Competitevenss since October 2019. The following key results have been acheived during 2020 under the pillars 1 and 2:
Pillar 1: Regulatory Reform
Support for EU Approximation
The Project worked with the National Food Agency on the regulatory issues aimed at facilitation of approximation of Georgian food safety legislation with the EU requirements. Namely:
- Finalized development of guidelines for the inspectors specific to the honey processing sector (inspection check-list);
- Finalized development of the regulatory requirements for the apiary/hive identification;
- Participated in discussion on updating the list of compulsory notifiable diseases and tests for beekeeping based on experience of various countries, such as Germany, Poland, UK, USA, Canada;
- Developed Manual on Fruit Juice and Other Similar Products Intended for Human Consumption in accordance with the Regulation #536 of the Government of Georgia dated 08.12.2017;
- Developed Manual on Managing Non-food By-products of Animal Origin for the slaughterhouses.
Flexible Implementation
Following development and further approval of the Government Regulation #14 on the Rules for Disorganized Production of Food/Feed, the Project started discussing the need for drafting the flexible hygiene and HACCP requirements with the Ministry of Environment Protection and Agriculture (MEPA), including defining the criteria for applicable business-operators. The Project developed the following two reports and submitted them to MEPA to define further actions in this direction 1) Policy Brief on the Possibility of Application of Flexible / Simplified Approach in Georgian Food Safety Legislation and 2) Brief Analysis of Flexibility in EU Legislation.
Opening New Markets
National Honey Monitoring Program being implemented during the last years by the NFA showed positive trend in considerable improvement of Georgian honey safety. Nevertheless, Georgian honey export to advanced markets and especially to the EU continued remaining at the very low level. Due to Covid-19 related worldwide restrictions certain activities such as participation of Georgian producers in international food fairs could not be implemented.
Nevertheless, significant accomplishment had been achieved in facilitation of exporting Georgian honey to the EU market.
One of the Project’s beekeepers had been contacted by an exporting company searching for Georgian honey for Italian market.  After visiting the honey processing facility and checking honey against the quality and safety parameters, agreement had been reached for purchase of 10,090 kg of honey of 2020 season intended for Italian market. The Project supported and guided the beekeeper and the exporter through the export documentation preparation process. Despite the fact that NFA was very supportive from the very start of this process, several challenges had appeared while preparing and transporting the shipment to the EU (such as mismatch of veterinary certificate template effective in the EU for beekeeping products imported from the third countries and the template approved for the export to the EU in Georgian legislation and lack of clear understanding in relation to the registration of producers/exporters in the EU traces system). As a result of effective cooperation between the Project, MEPA and NFA, all these challenges had been resolved in due course and Georgian honey had been received by the buyer in Italy on December 30, 2020. This first shipment of such a considerable amount of Georgian honey to the EU is expected to serve a positive example for other producers, exporters and importers to facilitate exporting of honey from Georgia to the EU.  
Pillar 2: Capacity Building and Awareness Creation
Technical Assistance to the Beekeepers and Honey Processors
The Project continued working with the selected beekeepers/honey processors in various regions of Georgia. Due to Covid-19 restrictions on-site consultancy could not be performed and the Project had been providing the beekeepers with only off-site consultancy in beekeeping and food safety issues, covering regulatory requirements as well. In particular this included ongoing monitoring of activities implemented by the beekeepers, such as:
- Adjusting food safety documentation and record keeping practices to their individual operations;
- Guiding beekepers on implementing the appropriate food safety regulatory requirements to become compliant for the NFA’s approval (considering their specific individual needs for improvements, e.g. facility remodeling to ensure adequate process flow, infrastructure arrangements, hygiene practices, record-keeping, product labelling, Covid-19 specific control measures, etc.);
- Guiding the beekeepers in good apiary management practices, including veterinary control and record-keeping;
- Discussing branding concept and retail package label design for the processors (Photo 1);
- Finalizing structure of the website aimed at supporting awareness increase on the modern beekeeping and food safety issues and web publicity of advanced honey producers;
- Drafting the content of the website as well the concept and requirements for the quality mark “Green Hive” for reliable Georgian honey.
To verify effectiveness of implemented activities, the Project cooperates with the NFA on testing the beneficiary beekeepers’ honey samples for unauthorized residues within the National Honey Monitoring Program.
Accomplishments:
The following accomplishments had been achieved:
- 2 beekeepers finalized construction of new honey processing facility;
- 4 honey processors were awarded the status of the approved establishment by the NFA;
- 7 hour food safety (GMP, GHP and HACCP) training was delivered to the participating beekeepers;
Technical assistance to the State Laboratory of Agriculture (SLA)
SLA staff continued practicing the honey testing methods which had been introduced with IFC support during the previous periods.
- SLA had been contracted by the NFA for testing 100 honey samples collected from the beekeepers countrywide within the National Honey Monitoring Program in 2020. Out of total 16 groups of substances to be monitored, 12 groups were tested by SLA, while only 4 groups were outsourced to Latvian lab.
- In addition, testing methods for the following 4 groups of compounds had been validated: Organochlorine pesticides; Organophosphorus compounds; Carbamates and Polychlorbiphenyls.
